ise, Picardie, France":"Noyon, Oise, Picardie, France","Montfort-l'Amaury, Yvelines, Île-de-France, France":"Montfort-l'Amaury, Yvelines, Île-de-France, France","Île-de-France, France":"Île-de-France, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"des","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["North German (<b>Düs</b>):","topographic name from Westphalian dialect <i>dūs</i> ‘pile, decay’.","variant of   Duis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Duis","meanings":["North German and Dutch: from a personal name derived from the name <i>Theodorus</i> (see   Theodore  ) or from a personal name based on the ancient Germanic element <i>theud</i> ‘people, race’."]}]},{"name":"Barres","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: unexplained. This surname, which originates from Eich in Rhineland-Palatinate, is rare in Germany.","French (southern) and Catalan: from a derivative of Occitan and Catalan <i>barda</i>, Old French <i>barde</i> ‘pack-saddle’.","French (<b>Bardès</b>): habitational name for someone from any of several minor places called Bard, from the Gaulish element <i>barro</i> ‘height, hill’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"son","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Ronald .  It is sometimes used as a given name in its own right."],"variants":[{"name":"Ronald","meanings":["From the Old Norse personal name <i>Rögnvaldr</i> (composed of <i>regin</i> ‘advice, decision’ (also, ‘the gods’) + <i>valdr</i> ‘ruler’). This name was regularly used in the Middle Ages in northern England and Scotland, where Scandinavian influence was strong. It is now widespread throughout the English-speaking world."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Guillaume II “l'Achille de son temps” des Barres was born in 1130, in Île-de-France, France as the son of Guillaume Ier DES BARRES. He married Hélissente de Chaumont Dame de Chaumont-sur-Yonne, Quenne, Augy et Chitry in 1168. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1180, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1130–1180":"1130–1180","1145–1216":"1145–1216","1153–1234":"1153–1234","1170–1235":"1170–1235","1105–1161":"1105–1161","1216":"1216","1105":"1105","1235":"1235","1168":"1168","1234":"1234","1145":"1145","1153":"1153","1130":"1130","1161":"1161","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","Noyon, Oise, Picardie, France":"Noyon, Oise, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Montfort-l'Amaury, Yvelines, Île-de-France, France":"Montfort-l'Amaury, Yvelines, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Île-de-France, France":"Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1130–1180":"1130–1180","1145–1216":"1145–1216","1153–1234":"1153–1234","1170–1235":"1170–1235","1105–1161":"1105–1161","1216":"1216","1105":"1105","1235":"1235","116